.IX Title "XVATTR 1"
.TH XVATTR 1 "perl v5.6.1" "2002-06-13" "User Commands"
.UC
.SH "NAME"
xvattr \- Query/Set X11 XVideo \fISetting\fR\|(s)
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
\&\fBxvattr\fR [\fIoptions\fR...] 
.PP
This program is used for getting and setting X11 Xv attributes such as
\&\s-1XV_BRIGHTNESS\s0, \s-1XV_CONTRAST\s0, \s-1XV_SATURATION\s0, \s-1XV_HUE\s0, \s-1XV_COLORKEY\s0, ...
.PP
For this program to work, you must have a version of X11 with the
XVideo extension and a graphics card that has Xv graphics acceleration.
.PP
Note: On some cards \s-1XV_BRIGHTNESS\s0 and \s-1XV_CONTRAST\s0 are not listed among
the available attributes, but they can still be set/changed.
.Sh "\s-1OPTIONS\s0"
.IX Subsection "OPTIONS"
With no options, all parameters are displayed. 
.PP
Long options are handled by \s-1GNU\s0 getopts and follow those rules. In
particular, options that are specified with a double dash (\-\-) rather
than a single dash (\-), can be abbreviated as long as they are
unique. Long parameters that need a value specified may have the
parameter and the value separated with blank space or an optional
equals sign (and no intervening space).
.PP
For example the following are all equivalent:
.PP
xvattr \-a \s-1XV_BRIGHTNESS\s0
xvattr \-\-attribute \s-1XV_BRIGHTNESS\s0
xvattr \-\-att \s-1XV_BRIGHTNESS\s0
xvattr \-\-att=XV_BRIGHTNESS
.PP
Example:
.PP
.Vb 9
\&  > xvattr
\&  Adaptor: 0
\&  Name: Matrox G-Series Backend Scaler
\&   Port: 46
\&    Name: XV_COLORKEY
\&     Flags: XvGettable XvSettable 
\&     Min value: 0
\&     Max value: 16777215
\&     Current value: 66046
.Ve
.Ip "{\-a | \-\-attribute} \fIattribute name\fR" 4
.IX Item "{-a | --attribute} attribute name"
Show value of attribute \fIattribute name\fR
.Sp
Example:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&  > xvattr -a XV_BRIGHTNESS
\&  XV_BRIGHTNESS = 24
.Ve
\&\&
.Ip "{\-a | \-\-attribute} \fIattribute name\fR [\-v | \-\-value] \fIvalue\fR" 4
.IX Item "{-a | --attribute} attribute name [-v | --value] value"
Set attribute \fIattribute name\fR to value \fIvalue\fR.
.Sp
Example:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&  > xvattr -a XV_COLORKEY -v 10
\&  XV_COLORKEY set to 10
.Ve
\&\&
.Ip "{\-p | \-\-port} \fIport number\fR" 4
.IX Item "{-p | --port} port number"
Get the attribute on the specified port.  If \-p is not set, the first
available port is used.
.Sp
Example:
.Sp
.Vb 20
\&  > xvattr -p 66
\&  Found Xv 2.2
\&  Adaptor: 0
\&  Name: SIS Video Overlay
\&   Port: 66
\&    Name: XV_COLORKEY
\&     Flags: XvGettable XvSettable 
\&     Min value: 0
\&     Max value: 16777215
\&     Current value: 66046
\&    Name: XV_BRIGHTNESS
\&     Flags: XvGettable XvSettable 
\&     Min value: -128
\&     Max value: 127
\&     Current value: 0
\&    Name: XV_CONTRAST
\&     Flags: XvGettable XvSettable 
\&     Min value: 0
\&     Max value: 255
\&     Current value: 128
.Ve
